\begin{abstract}

Large Language Models (LLMs) have achieved strong performance on tasks such as clinical summarization, question-answering, and clinical diagnosis on medical reasoning benchmarks such as MedQA, yet their deployment remains constrained by opacity and unverifiable decision paths.

We introduce \textbf{Trust-X}, a framework that embeds explainability, consensus reasoning, and real-time safety oversight to evaluate how transparently language models reason through diagnostic problems.

Trust-X integrates multiple reasoning agents, safety monitoring agents, and quantitative trust indices that combine reasoning stability and operational safety.

Across 50 clinical scenarios, Trust-X maintained stable diagnostic accuracy ($\approx68%$) while revealing that models can appear correct yet reason unreliably.

These findings suggest that reliability in clinical AI emerges from transparency and accountability rather than accuracy alone.

\keywords{Large Language Models \and Explainable AI \and Trustworthy AI \and Medical Diagnosis \and Multi-Agent Systems}

\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Large Language Models (LLMs) such as GPT-4 \cite{achiam2023gpt}, Gemini \cite{team2023gemini}, and Med-PaLM 2 \cite{singhal2025toward} have demonstrated remarkable progress in natural language reasoning across domains including medicine.

They now perform at near-clinician levels on medical benchmarks \cite{kung2023performance,nori2023capabilities}. However, their deployment in healthcare remains constrained by opaque reasoning and unreliable decision paths.

Medicine requires not only correct predictions but also \emph{explainable and justifiable reasoning}. Clinicians evaluate whether conclusions follow medical logic and evidence.

Despite improvements in alignment and safety training, LLMs still show instability in reasoning and excessive confidence in uncertain cases.

These limitations motivated the development of \textbf{Trust-X}, a framework designed to make reasoning transparent, inspectable, and measurable.

Trust-X introduces four core features:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Consensus Reasoning:} Multiple doctor agents independently analyze each case and vote on the diagnosis.
\item \textbf{Reasoning Trace:} Each step records the evidence, reasoning, and conclusion.
\item \textbf{End-to-End Logging:} All actions are recorded for reproducibility.
\item \textbf{Trust Scoring:} Reasoning quality and safety behavior are combined into quantitative trust indices.
\end{itemize}

Rather than claiming to make LLMs trustworthy, Trust-X measures when trust emerges and when it fails.

\section{Related Work}

Explainable AI techniques such as LIME \cite{ribeiro2016should}, SHAP \cite{lundberg2017unified}, and Grad-CAM \cite{selvaraju2017grad} attempt to reveal model reasoning.

However, these approaches struggle in medical contexts where reasoning unfolds through dialogue and evidence accumulation.

Recent work on chain-of-thought reasoning \cite{wei2022chain} and reflection-based prompting attempts to expose reasoning steps, but these explanations may not reflect genuine reasoning processes.

Trust-X addresses this limitation by logging the reasoning process in real time rather than reconstructing explanations post-hoc.

\section{Methodology}

Trust-X models diagnostic reasoning as interactions between specialized agents.

\subsection{Multi-Agent Diagnostic Simulation}

The system includes four agent types:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Doctor Agent} – performs diagnostic reasoning.
\item \textbf{Patient Agent} – provides patient responses.
\item \textbf{Measurement Agent} – returns diagnostic test results.
\item \textbf{Safety Agent} – monitors medical actions for risks.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Consensus Disagreement Rate}

Diagnostic uncertainty is captured through the Consensus Disagreement Rate (CDR):

[
\mathrm{CDR}i = 1 - \frac{\max{d \in D_i} f_i(d)}{K}
]

where (f_i(d)) is the number of agents predicting diagnosis (d).

\section{Trust Metrics}

Trust-X introduces three indices:

\begin{itemize}
\item Epistemic Trust Index (ETI)
\item Operational Safety Index (OSI)
\item Final Trust Index (FTI)
\end{itemize}

[
\mathrm{ETI} = 0.4 \times Accuracy + 0.3 \times (1-CDR) + 0.3 \times RDC
]

[
\mathrm{OSI} = 100 - 0.5(UnsafeRx + TestAlerts)
]

[
\mathrm{FTI} = 0.5 \times (ETI + OSI)
]

\section{Algorithm}

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Computation of Trust Metrics}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\For{each clinical case}
\State Collect diagnoses from all agents
\State Compute majority vote
\State Calculate CDR
\State Compute reasoning similarity (RDC)
\State Compute ETI
\State Compute OSI
\State Compute final trust index FTI
\EndFor
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\section{Results}

Experiments were conducted on 50 clinical diagnostic cases derived from the MedQA dataset.

Across all configurations diagnostic accuracy remained stable around 68–69%.

However trust metrics varied significantly depending on reasoning transparency and safety monitoring.

